<DOC><DOCNO> AP881104-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-88 0820EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-EasternCocaine     11-04 0236</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Eastern Cocaine,0241</SECOND><HEAD>Customs Fines Eastern, But Doesn't Seize Plane</HEAD><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines says it will contest a $1 millionfine imposed after federal agents found cocaine aboard one of itsjets for the second time in as many weeks.   ``We have one of the most comprehensive programs in the industryto intercept drugs,'' said spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak. ``We spendthree and a half million dollars a year.''   The Customs Service on Monday found 68 pounds of cocaine aboard aflight from Colombia hidden in a box of ground coffee in the baggagecompartment. On Thursday, the agency fined the airline but did notimpound the Boeing 727.   ``Customs, at the present time, is not seizing the 727, sinceEastern appears to be making serious efforts to improve its securitymeasures against drug smuggling,'' said Customs spokesman CliffStallings.   Last week, Customs seized an Eastern L-1011 and fined the airline$896,000 after finding 56 pounds of cocaine in a mail bag. Easternprotested the seizure of the plane, saying its tip led to thediscovery of the drugs, but Customs denied that.   The plane was released after Eastern posted bond for the value ofthe fine.   Ms. Ceremsak said that despite the recent seizures, Eastern hasno plans to discontinue service to Latin America and the Caribbean.The Colombian national airline, Avianca, ended all cargo flightsafter repeated drug seizures on its planes.</TEXT></DOC>